      "lineNbr": 6,
      "author": {
        "id": 10009
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-27T20:14:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In google3 it\u0027s fairly typical for an RPC named Foo to take a FooRequest message and return a FooResponse message, even if FooResponse has just one single field, e.g. of type AutoRollMiniStatuses.\n\nSome benefits of this pattern include:\n\n- More future proof: It decouples the RPC request/response from the underlying message. For example, today GetRollersResponse might include just one field of type AutoRollMiniStatuses, tomorrow GetRollersResponse could include something else entirely.\n\n- Easier for the reader to follow: any references to GetRollersResponse in code indicate to the reader that said code pertains to the GetRollers RPC, whereas a shared response message such as AutoRollMiniStatuses does not carry this information.\n\n- Nicer tests: inputs are always of type FooRequest, expected/actual outputs are always of type FooResponse.\n\n- Easy to find all usages of the RPC: just search / grep for \"FooRequest\" or \"FooResponse\".\n\nThis is what things would look like if you accept my suggestion:\n\n  service AutoRollService {\n    rpc GetRollers(GetRollersRequest) returns (GetRollersResponse);\n    ...\n  }\n\n  ...\n\n  message GetRollersRequest {}\n\n  message GetRollersResponse {\n    AutoRollMiniStatuses statuses \u003d 1;\n\n    // Or alternatively:\n    repeated AutoRollMiniStatus statuses \u003d 1;\n  }\n\nSame for the other RPCs.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 6,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 6,
        "endChar": 65
      },
      "revId": "1e6ac7eca5a8312aee18d88478ee8aa272bd1e3a",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
